sec.p:
Some machinery manufacturers design special heat seal jaws for sealing BOPP. It is necessary to have good temperature control, since BOPP’s sealing range is narrower than regenerated cellulose film or polyester-based laminates. Sehyun4 studied some relationships among polymer characteristics, processability, and BOPP film properties. The effectiveness of the heat seal depends upon three main factors.5–7


Dwell time: The options here are limited since this depends on synchronization with other production machines. Providing the sealant layer with the broadest possible temperature sealing range certainly helps to broaden the possible dwell times.

Sealing pressure: This, in most cases, depends upon adjustments by a skilled operator, since either low or excess pressure can lead to imperfect seals. The pressure itself in all cases depends upon the film or laminate thickness used. With higher pressure, shrinkage occurs in the seal area, resulting in the sealant layer thinning. Nicastro et al.8 investigated change in crystallinity during heat sealing of CPP film and showed that for a CPP, the percent crystallinity in the sealed area increased with increased sealing temperature and the dwell time and sealing pressure had little effect.

Sealing temperature: Of all factors, the temperature is perhaps the most important factor since excess temperature can result in:


film deorientation;

breakdown of laminates;

sticking in the sealing jaws;

brittle seals;

thinning out of sealing layer; and

film shrinkage.
